records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jenelle Owens in court with attorney Enku Edgar Lin.  Timothy J. Cotter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

  Sentencing proceeds. Statements made by the State, defense counsel and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT 1:  Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 3 YEARS.  
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 1-1/2 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 1-1/2  YEARS. 
Credit given for 1 day time served if revoked.

Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Court finds defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program IF DEEMED APPROPRIATE BY WISCONSIN DEPARTMENT OF CORRECTIONS.

COURT STAYS sentence and places defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS under the supervision of Wisconsin Department of Corrections.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION (AS TO COUNT 1):
* Comply with the standard rules of probation/extended supervision.
* SERVE 45 DAYS "condition time" at the House of Correction with release privileges for employment and treatment purposes only - STAYED until 07-20-2015 at 12:00 PM.  Court ordered "GOOD TIME CREDIT" to apply towards the condition time.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* Provide a DNA sample and PAY DNA surcharge - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges  - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY restitution in the amount of $5,000.00 payable to the victim, Rosie S. - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Court ordered the Dosage Probation Program.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Appeal rights given.

Defendant Jenelle Owens in court with attorney Enku Edgar Lin.  Timothy J. Cotter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to her plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised she is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised she is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
